In article <2hgk4jINNdho@mailhost.uni-koblenz.de>,
Rainer Schmitz <schmitz@lalo.uni-koblenz.de> wrote:
> Let's think about
[the one-time pad].

> Of course, this crypt will take information to decode it, because it uses no
> key.

No, the random data IS the key.

> Now, you join the the first (random) cryption with the second (real)
> encryption. Now you got a new encryption method.

In this case, you have the security of the one-time pad plus the
security of the real encryption.  But so what?  Since the one-time pad
gives perfect security on its own, there is no need to add any
superencipherment.


